 🛠️ Step 1.5: Get Ollama running

  Part A — Install the Ollama app (this is the "server"):

  1. Go to ollama.com/download → download the Windows installer
  2. Run it (normal "next, next, finish" install)

  Part A — Install the Ollama app (this is the "server"):

  1. Go to ollama.com/download → download the Windows installer
  2. Run it (normal "next, next, finish" install)
  3. After installing, it runs quietly in the background (you'll see a little llama icon in your system tray)

  Part B — Download a model (this is the "brain"). Back in your terminal, type:

  ollama pull llama3.2

  This downloads Llama 3.2 — a small (~2 GB) but capable model from Meta. It runs on most laptops and, importantly, supports tool-calling, which 
  we'll need when we build the real agent. The download takes a few minutes.

  Part C — Test it works (talk to the model right in your terminal):

  ollama run llama3.2

  You'll get a >>> prompt. Type something like hello, who are you? and watch it answer — that's an AI model running on your own machine, offline.
  🎉 Type /bye to exit.

  Part D — Install the JS client so our code can talk to it:

  npm install ollama

  This ollama npm package is a clean wrapper around that localhost:11434 server — same idea as axios wrapping HTTP calls, but purpose-built for  
  Ollama.

 💻 Step 2: Your first "Hello, Agent"

  This is a plain chat with the model — no tools yet. We crawl before we walk. Create a new file in your hello-agent folder called hello.js, and
  type this in (don't paste — typing it makes it stick):
  
  import ollama from 'ollama'

  const response = await ollama.chat({
    model: 'llama3.2',
    messages: [
      { role: 'user', content: 'Hello! In one sentence, who are you?' }
    ],
  })

  console.log(response.message.content)

  🔍 Every line, explained

  import ollama from 'ollama'
  Brings in the package you installed. ollama is now an object with methods that talk to your local server — just like import express from       
  'express'.

  const response = await ollama.chat({ ... })
  The whole game is right here. ollama.chat(...) sends your message to the model and waits for a reply. It's an async call (it goes to
  localhost:11434 and back), so we await it — exactly like awaiting a fetch or a Mongo query. (await works at the top level here because we set  
  "type": "module".)

  model: 'llama3.2',
  Which brain to use — the model you pulled earlier. If you'd pulled others, you'd pick here.

  messages: [
    { role: 'user', content: 'Hello! In one sentence, who are you?' }
  ],
  This is the most important concept to absorb. You don't send a plain string — you send an array of messages, each with a role and content.     
  Right now there's one message from you (role: 'user').

  Why an array? Because this is how the model "remembers" a conversation — every back-and-forth is another item in this list. The roles are:     
  - user → you
  - assistant → the AI
  - system → instructions that shape the AI's behavior (we'll use this later)

  Memorize this shape — it's identical across Ollama, Claude, OpenAI, everything. Learn it once, use it everywhere.

  console.log(response.message.content)
  The model's reply comes back as an object. The actual text is at response.message.content — we just print it.


  Step 3


  🪄 Step 3: The magic moment — give it a tool
  
  Right now your model is a chatbot — it can only talk. Watch what happens when we hand it a tool.

  Remember the key idea I told you earlier: the model can't run your code — it can only ask you to. You're about to see that happen with your own
  eyes.

  Create a new file called agent.js and type this in:

  import ollama from 'ollama'

  // 1. Describe a tool the model is ALLOWED to use
  const tools = [
    {
      type: 'function',
      function: {
        name: 'get_weather',
        description: 'Get the current weather for a given city',
        parameters: {
          type: 'object',
          properties: {
            city: { type: 'string', description: 'The name of the city' },
          },
          required: ['city'],
        },
      },
    },
  ]

  // 2. Ask a question that NEEDS the tool
  const response = await ollama.chat({
    model: 'llama3.2',
    messages: [
      { role: 'user', content: "What's the weather in Tokyo right now?" },
    ],
    tools: tools,
  })

  // 3. See what the model decided to do
  console.log(JSON.stringify(response.message.tool_calls, null, 2))

  🔍 What's new here, explained

  The tools array — this is just a description of a function, written as JSON. We are NOT giving the model the actual code. We're handing it a   
  menu that says "a tool called get_weather exists, here's what it does, and it needs a city." Notice the pieces:

  - name → what the tool is called
  - description → this is critical — the model reads this plain-English sentence to decide when this tool is useful. Good descriptions = smart   
  agents.
  - parameters → what inputs the tool needs, written in JSON Schema (the same kind of schema you'd write for validating an API body or a Mongoose
  model). Here: one required city string.

  tools: tools — we pass that menu along with the question. Now the model knows it has the option to use a tool.

  response.message.tool_calls — here's the payoff. When you give the model tools, instead of replying with text, it can reply with a request to  
  call a tool. That request lands in tool_calls.

  import ollama from 'ollama';

const tools =[
    {
        type:"function",
        function:{
            name:"getWeather",
            description:"Get the weather for a given city",
            parameters:{
                type:"object",
                properties:{
                    city:{
                        type:"string",
                        description:"The city to get the weather for",

                    },
                },
                required:["city"],
            }
        }
    }
]

const response = await ollama.chat({
    model:"llama3.2",
    messages:[
        {role:"user",content:"What's the weather in Hyderabad?"}
    ],
    tools:tools,
})

console.log(JSON.stringify(response.message.tool_calls,null,2))


